<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
The species in this genus are probably polyphagous, and have been associated mainly with plants in the 
<taxonomicName genus="Ericaceae" lsidName="Ericaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Ericaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="Asteraceae" lsidName="Asteraceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Polygonaceae" lsidName="Polygonaceae" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="genus">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="An essay about the relationships between the leaf-beetles and their food-plants. Backhuys Publishers, Leiden" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" title="Host-plants of Chrysomelidae of the World." year="1995">Jolivet and Hawkeswood 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Seven species are known from the Mascarene Islands and about ten, as yet undescribed, from Madagascar (personal data).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
